scoring_metadata.calibration_reference: v3-4_normalized top 20 + v3-5 EC rerate top 50
scoring_metadata.calibration_notes: Existing top models: V3-FEAR-001 84.0 (SW), V3-DEF-001 81.0 (SW), V3-DEF-003 81.75 (SW), V3-EMRG-001 80.5 (SW). STRUCTURAL_WINNER requires composite >= 80.0 AND SN >= 9.0 per hard enforcement thresholds. Very few cards should qualify. Most deep dive cards expected in 60-75 range (CONDITIONAL to FORCE_RIDER). Defense cards skew higher due to $13.4B dedicated budget and geopolitical urgency. Education cards skew lower due to fear friction (gap=5) constraining adoption timing.
scoring_metadata.scoring_method: 5-axis manual scoring with QCEW data lookup, calibrated against existing inventory

scored_cards.model_name: RegTech Orchestration Layer for Alternative Investment Compliance

SN.justification: Baumol 3.59x with 104K establishments creates massive Baumol energy. 5% employment growth compounds compliance demand. Regulatory requirements are non-negotiable. But not economy-level structural necessity — this is one financial subsector.

FA.justification: Strong F1 (9/10 - AI regulatory parsing), F4 (8/10 - PE refinancing wall), F5 (7/10 - 73% finserv AI adoption), F3 (6/10 - multi-jurisdiction). 4 forces, 3 strong.

EC.justification: Supply chain low risk (software). Regulatory contagion high (SEC rulemaking is the driver). Competitive moderate (5 funded entrants). Leading indicators strong. Talent flow moderate (CPA pipeline -33% but compliance professionals available).

TG.justification: Window open NOW with SEC rulemaking velocity at peak. Crash resilient — compliance demand counter-cyclical. Perez frenzy phase for finserv AI.

CE.justification: $2-8M capital, 4mo to revenue, 82% gross margins. Survives funding freeze. 80-120 firm break-even is achievable. Strong cost advantage ratio (8-12x).

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 78.75 >= 70.0 and FA 8.0 >= 7.0. Does not meet STRUCTURAL_WINNER threshold (SN < 9.0).

scored_cards.model_name: AI-Optimized Custom Compute Hardware Foundry

SN.justification: Baumol 3.76x is extreme but only 2,387 establishments and 162K employees — concentrated sector. AI inference hardware demand is real (40%+ CAGR). CHIPS Act creates subsidy window. But acquisition + retooling is execution-heavy.

FA.justification: 5 forces aligned: F1 (9), F3 (9 — CHIPS Act + reshoring), F4 (7 — VC rotation to hardtech), F6 (6 — energy constraint), F2 (5 — Silver Tsunami owners). Strong multi-force convergence.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (CHIPS Act subsidies but hardware dependencies). Regulatory strong (ITAR creates moat). Competitive low (2 funded entrants). International context very strong (US-China decoupling drives reshoring premium). Critical minerals risk from China export controls tempers slightly.

TG.justification: Arbitrage window 2026-2028 before CHIPS Act fabs create demand spike. Medium crash resilience — defense demand counter-cyclical but consumer hardware cyclical.

CE.justification: $5-25M capital required is substantial. 6mo to revenue but 35% gross margins are low for AI-adjacent. Hardware play with real asset backing but capital-intensive.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 74.0 >= 70.0, FA 8.0 >= 7.0. Also qualifies as TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 7.5, close but not >= 8.0).

scored_cards.model_name: IT Services Engagement Intelligence Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 2.05x with 405K establishments and 2.46M employees — massive sector. 5% wage growth vs flat employment is classic Baumol disease. Data compounding thesis is compelling but unproven at scale. IT services is non-discretionary for enterprises.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI coding agents), F4 (7 — PE margin pressure), F2 (6 — Silver Tsunami knowledge loss), F5 (5 — cultural receptivity but resistance to automation exposure). 4 forces, 2 strong.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (LLM API dependency). No strong regulatory driver. Competitive import moderate (4 funded entrants). Indian IT services firms (Infosys, Wipro) create international competitive pressure. Talent available.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. Medium crash resilience — IT spending partially discretionary. Data compounding takes 500-1000 engagements to show value, which takes time.

CE.justification: $3-10M capital, 6mo to revenue, 78% gross margins. Survives funding freeze. Cost advantage compounds over time (3-5x after 1000 engagements). Strong SaaS economics.

scored_cards.model_name: AI-Native Fund Administration and Operations Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 3.13x with highest fragmentation in dataset (0.42 — 2.4 employees per firm). 10% employment growth means demand outrunning capacity. Fund admin is non-discretionary. Only 18K employees but 7,731 establishments — extreme fragmentation creates AI opportunity.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — rules-based processes), F4 (8 — new fund formation), F5 (7 — 73% finserv adoption), F3 (5 — multi-jurisdiction). 4 forces, 2 very strong.

EC.justification: Multi-jurisdiction compliance (Cayman, Luxembourg) adds EC value. But small sector (18K employees) limits international scale. Audit firm acceptance uncertainty. Low competitive import (3 funded entrants).

TG.justification: Window 2026-2027. High crash resilience — fund admin mandatory regardless of market. Counter-cyclical: crash drives cost-cutting demand. Fast entry (3mo to revenue).

CE.justification: $1-5M capital, 3mo to revenue, 88% gross margins — best unit economics in the batch. 40-60 fund break-even. Survives funding freeze. 5-8x cost advantage over incumbents.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 77.25 >= 70.0, FA 7.5 >= 7.0. Also qualifies as CAPITAL_MOAT (CE 9.0 >= 9.0 and SN 8.0 >= 6.0).

scored_cards.model_name: Cobot-Integrated Electronics Assembly Line Modernizer

SN.justification: Same QCEW data as 3341-001 (Baumol 3.76x, 2387 establishments). Cobot ROI math is strong ($25-60K vs $273K worker). 78-point manufacturing readiness gap (98% exploring, 20% deployed) confirms demand. But narrow target market (2,387 facilities).

FA.justification: F1 (10 — proven cobot + AI vision tech), F3 (8 — CHIPS Act reshoring), F2 (7 — aging workforce), F6 (5 — energy optimization), F4 (6 — VC to physical). 5 forces, 2 very strong.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (cobots sourced from Universal Robots/FANUC/ABB — international). CHIPS Act 25% ITC is strong regulatory tailwind. Competitive moderate (6 entrants). International context strong for reshoring.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. Medium crash resilience — capex can be deferred. But wage pressure trajectory ($273K growing 4.8%/yr) creates urgency even in downturn.

CE.justification: $3-15M capital, 4mo to revenue, but only 45% gross margins — this is a physical deployment business, not SaaS. 8-15 factory deployments/yr for break-even. Capital-intensive.

scored_cards.model_name: AI Lab Notebook and Experiment Intelligence Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 2.30x with 55,600 establishments and 923K employees. 4% employment growth. Reproducibility crisis (70% failure rate) is real structural problem. But lab workflow change is slow and adoption friction is high among conservative scientists.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — LLM parsing + pattern detection), F2 (6 — retiring researchers), F4 (6 — AI-for-science VC), F5 (5 — scientist conservatism dampens). 4 forces but only 1 very strong.

EC.justification: Supply chain low risk (SaaS). No strong regulatory driver (FDA acceptance is positive but not mandatory). 7 funded entrants — emerging competitive field. International pharma R&D provides export potential.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. High crash resilience (pharma pipelines can't pause, defense R&D counter-cyclical). But academic labs are budget-constrained, slowing adoption.

CE.justification: $2-8M capital, 6mo to revenue, 80% gross margins. 150-250 lab subscriptions for break-even. Strong SaaS economics. Survives funding freeze.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 69.5 >= 60.0 but < 70.0. FA 7.0 meets FORCE_RIDER threshold but composite is below 70. Assigned CONDITIONAL as composite < 70.

scored_cards.model_name: Mortgage and Loan Servicing AI Operations Platform

SN.justification: Most extreme labor market signal: 13.8% wage growth AND -10.7% employment decline simultaneously. Baumol 1.90x with 34,602 establishments. The sector is hemorrhaging workers — AI is structurally necessary just to keep operations running. Loan servicing is non-discretionary.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI document processing at 95%+ accuracy), F4 (8 — PE refinancing wall), F5 (7 — 73% finserv adoption), F3 (4 — CFPB regulatory). 4 forces, 2 very strong.

EC.justification: Supply chain low risk (software). CFPB regulatory creates both compliance demand and risk. Competitive moderate (5 entrants). Limited international dimension (US mortgage market is domestic). Leading indicators strong (workforce exodus data).

TG.justification: Window 2026-2027. High crash resilience — loan servicing is counter-cyclical (more defaults = more servicing work). 3mo to revenue. Window urgent given workforce exodus pace.

CE.justification: $1.5-6M capital, 3mo to revenue, 85% gross margins. 10-15x cost advantage. Survives funding freeze. Best cost advantage ratio in the batch. Break-even at 200-500K loans.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 78.5 >= 70.0, FA 7.5 >= 7.0. Also qualifies as CAPITAL_MOAT (CE 9.0 >= 9.0, SN 8.5 >= 6.0) and TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 8.0 >= 8.0).

scored_cards.model_name: Semiconductor Test and Packaging Automation Integrator

SN.justification: Baumol 1.97x with 395K employees. CHIPS Act test/packaging bottleneck is real (80%+ in Asia). Every chip must be tested. But this is a capital-intensive acquisition play requiring $10-50M.

FA.justification: F3 (10 — US-China chip controls make this strategic), F1 (8 — AI test optimization), F4 (7 — CHIPS Act ITC + VC), F6 (5 — energy), F2 (5 — aging engineers). 5 forces, 2 very strong. Strongest geopolitical alignment of any v35 card.

EC.justification: International context is THE story: 80% of advanced packaging in Asia creates the entire value proposition. CHIPS Act subsidies. ITAR requirements for defense chips. International competitive dynamics directly drive demand. High leading indicator transfer from CHIPS Act fab timelines.

TG.justification: Arbitrage window 2026-2028 before CHIPS Act fabs come online. High crash resilience (CHIPS Act committed, defense counter-cyclical). But timing depends on CHIPS Act fab construction schedules.

CE.justification: $10-50M capital — most capital-intensive card in the batch. 8mo to revenue. Only 40% gross margins. Break-even at 5-10M chips/month. Real asset backing but capital requirements are substantial.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 74.25 >= 70.0, FA 8.0 >= 7.0. Also qualifies as TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 7.5 close but below 8.0 threshold).

scored_cards.model_name: AI Legal Document Factory for Small and Mid-Size Law Firms

SN.justification: Baumol 1.72x with 207K establishments and 1.18M employees — massive fragmented market. 60-70% of legal work is document-intensive. But 82% ethical concern rate is the HIGHEST fear friction of any professional sector, severely constraining adoption speed.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — LLM document processing), F2 (6 — retiring partners), F4 (5 — legal tech VC), F5 (4 — 82% ethical concern DEPRESSES this). Only 1 very strong force. Psychology is a negative force here.

EC.justification: No strong international dimension for US legal services. 15 funded entrants — CROWDED competitive field. Thomson Reuters/LexisNexis are powerful incumbents. Jurisdictional fragmentation (50 states) creates complexity. Low regulatory contagion (bar associations slow).

TG.justification: High crash resilience (legal work non-discretionary). But 82% ethical concern rate means adoption is slow despite clear economics. Window exists but friction delays realization.

CE.justification: $2-8M capital, 4mo to revenue, 82% gross margins. 300-500 firm subscriptions for break-even. Strong SaaS economics. 5-10x cost advantage.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 67.25, 60-70 range. FA 6.5 < 7.0 so not FORCE_RIDER. High fear friction constrains both FA and TG scores.

scored_cards.model_name: AI-Powered Reservoir and Production Optimization Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 2.84x with 6,396 establishments. Each 1% production improvement on a $5B field = $50M/year. Data center energy demand drives production necessity. But O&G is conservative and cyclical.

FA.justification: F6 (9 — data center grid demand), F1 (8 — ML sensor optimization), F3 (6 — energy independence), F4 (6 — O&G ETF rotation). 4 forces, 2 strong. Energy force alignment is strongest.

EC.justification: Strong international context: global oil markets, LNG export dynamics, OPEC supply dynamics all affect demand. 8 funded entrants. SLB/Halliburton are powerful incumbents. Basin-specific data creates moat.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. Medium crash resilience — oil prices volatile, but optimization tools more valuable at low prices. Conservative industry adoption speed tempers timing grade.

CE.justification: $3-12M capital, 6mo to revenue, 75% gross margins. 30-50 operator break-even. Good SaaS economics. 10-20x cost advantage vs petroleum engineers.

scored_cards.model_name: Contract Research Marketplace with AI Matching

SN.justification: Same QCEW sector as 5417-001. R&D outsourcing is a $100B+ market with real discovery problem. But marketplace businesses face cold-start problem and unproven product-market fit for this specific application.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI capability profiling), F4 (7 — pharma cost pressure), F2 (5 — retiring network holders), F5 (4 — procurement conservatism). 2 moderate forces, 1 strong.

EC.justification: International dimension moderate (global pharma R&D). 3 funded entrants (low competition). But Clarivate/IQVIA have existing data advantages. Marketplace liquidity risk is the key constraint.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. High crash resilience (pharma pipelines durable). But marketplace liquidity takes time to build — slow to reach tipping point. 8mo to revenue.

CE.justification: $3-10M capital, 8mo to revenue, 70% gross margins. 50-100 matched contracts/yr for break-even. Take rate model (5-8%) is proven in other marketplaces but unproven here.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 64.75, 60-70 range. FA 6.5 < 7.0. Marketplace cold-start risk constrains all scores.

scored_cards.model_name: Aerospace MRO Digital Thread and Predictive Maintenance Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 1.65x with 537K employees growing 7.5% YoY — one of fastest manufacturing expansions. Boeing/Airbus 14K aircraft backlog. MRO runs on paper. Aging workforce creates knowledge capture urgency.

FA.justification: F3 (9 — defense $2,718B + ITAR), F1 (8 — AI predictive maintenance), F2 (8 — mechanics averaging 55+), F4 (6 — VC to hard-tech), F6 (4 — fuel efficiency). 5 forces, 3 strong. Excellent multi-force convergence.

EC.justification: Strong international context: Boeing/Airbus global customers, NATO defense MRO demand, EASA regulatory alignment. ITAR creates moat. 6 funded entrants. FAA/EASA approval process is a moat but adds 18-36 month delay.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. High crash resilience (FAA mandated maintenance, defense counter-cyclical, fleet ages in downturns = more MRO). But 8mo to revenue and FAA approval timeline tempers.

CE.justification: $5-20M capital, 8mo to revenue, 65% gross margins. 200-500 tail numbers for break-even. More capital-intensive than pure SaaS but real asset value. Physical integration required.

scored_cards.model_name: AI-Augmented AEC Design and Permitting Accelerator

SN.justification: Baumol 1.51x — at the Baumol threshold, just compelling enough for AI automation. 167K establishments and 1.65M employees — massive market. Code compliance is rule-based and automatable. But Baumol score is low relative to top cards.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI code checking), F2 (7 — retiring engineers), F4 (6 — construction tech VC), F5 (5 — professional liability caution). 4 forces, 1 very strong. Good but not exceptional alignment.

EC.justification: Limited international dimension (building codes are local/US). 5 funded entrants. Autodesk/Bentley/Trimble are powerful platform incumbents who could bundle AI. Local code variation is both opportunity and challenge.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. Medium crash resilience — construction is cyclical but CHIPS Act + infrastructure bill provide committed pipeline. Residential may soften but commercial/industrial sustains.

CE.justification: $2-8M capital, 5mo to revenue, 80% gross margins. 300-500 firm subscriptions for break-even. Strong SaaS economics. 5-8x cost advantage for code compliance.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 68.5, 60-70 range. FA 7.0 meets FORCE_RIDER FA threshold but composite < 70.0.

scored_cards.model_name: Consulting Engagement Knowledge Compounding Engine

SN.justification: Baumol 1.61x with 395K establishments — most fragmented professional services. But only 1.9% wage growth suggests less Baumol pressure than other sectors. Consulting is partially discretionary. Knowledge compounding thesis is compelling but unproven.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — LLM research automation), F2 (7 — retiring partners), F4 (6 — PE margin pressure), F5 (5 — fear of replacement). 4 forces but only 1 strong. Consulting psychology (every client unique) resists systematization.

EC.justification: Limited international dimension for most consulting (domestic clients). 4 funded entrants (low competition). McKinsey/BCG/Bain could build internally. No regulatory driver.

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. LOW crash resilience — consulting is cut early in recessions. But AI consulting (transformation) grows counter-cyclically. Mixed timing signal.

CE.justification: $3-10M capital, 6mo to revenue, 75% gross margins. 300-500 firm subscriptions for break-even. Good SaaS economics. 3-5x cost advantage after 500 engagements (compounding effect).

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 63.75, 60-70 range. FA 6.5 < 7.0. Low crash resilience and unproven compounding thesis constrain scores.

scored_cards.model_name: Alternative Investment Firms Roll-Up with AI Back-Office

SN.justification: Same QCEW as 5239-001 (Baumol 3.59x). Silver Tsunami (52% owned by 55+) creates predictable acquisition pipeline. AI back-office consolidation math works (40% margin expansion). But execution-heavy roll-up model with integration risk.

FA.justification: F4 (9 — PE refinancing wall creates distressed sellers at 4-6x), F1 (9 — AI back-office), F2 (8 — demographic inevitability of forced sales), F5 (6 — 73% finserv adoption). 4 forces, 3 very strong.

EC.justification: Primarily domestic (US RIA market). Multi-jurisdiction for some fund types (Cayman, Luxembourg). 4 funded entrants. Focus Financial/Hightower/Dynasty are significant competitors in RIA roll-up space.

TG.justification: High crash resilience — downturns ACCELERATE acquisition opportunities (more distressed sellers, lower multiples). Counter-cyclical roll-up thesis. Window optimal now as Silver Tsunami accelerates.

CE.justification: $8-30M capital required — substantial. 3mo to revenue from Day 1 (acquired firms have existing revenue). 65% gross margins post-consolidation. But capital intensity for acquisitions is high.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 71.25 >= 70.0, FA 7.5 >= 7.0. Also TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 8.0 >= 8.0).

scored_cards.model_name: Pipeline Integrity and Operations AI Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 2.23x with 2,114 establishments. 6.1% wage growth signals acute labor scarcity. PHMSA regulations mandate integrity management. Pipeline safety is non-negotiable. Data center energy demand makes gas pipelines strategic infrastructure.

FA.justification: F6 (10 — data center grid demand makes pipelines bottleneck for AI scaling), F1 (8 — AI smart pig analysis and leak prediction), F2 (7 — retiring integrity engineers), F3 (6 — energy independence + TSA directive). 4 forces, 2 very strong.

EC.justification: Primarily domestic infrastructure (US pipeline network). TSA Pipeline Security Directive creates regulatory moat. 3 funded entrants (low competition). International dimension limited (some LNG export pipeline relevance).

TG.justification: Window 2026-2028. High crash resilience (pipeline safety federally mandated, cannot defer). PHMSA 2024 mega-rule creates immediate compliance demand. Data center demand is durable.

CE.justification: $3-12M capital, 6mo to revenue, 78% gross margins. 20-40 operator break-even. Good SaaS economics. 5-8x cost advantage for integrity analysis.

scored_cards.model_name: CMMC Compliance Automation Platform for Defense Contractors

SN.justification: 220K companies MUST certify — this is legally mandated. Only 60 C3PAOs for 220K companies = decade-long queue without automation. 15-20% of DIB expected to exit due to cost — AI preserves the industrial base. CMMC is in DFARS. Non-negotiable demand.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — LLM regulatory parsing), F3 (10 — CMMC exists because of adversary cyber threats), F4 (7 — defense tech VC). 3 forces, 2 at maximum. Geopolitical driver is absolute.

EC.justification: Supply chain minimal (software). Regulatory contagion is the DRIVER (9/10). Competitive moderate (12 funded entrants but no dominant AI-native). Leading indicators strong (CMMC contract solicitations). Resource talent moderate (cleared professionals needed).

TG.justification: Window OPEN NOW — CMMC enforcement ramping in 2026. High crash resilience (defense contractual requirement). First movers capture 220K-company wave. Very high time sensitivity.

CE.justification: $1-5M capital, 3mo to revenue, 80% gross margins. 100-150 subscriptions for break-even against 220K addressable. 5-10x cost advantage. Survives funding freeze. Exceptional unit economics.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 82.5 >= 80.0 but SN 8.5 < 9.0 per HARD ENFORCEMENT threshold. CMMC is mandatory for defense contractors but not the broader economy — this prevents SN from reaching 9.0. Reassigned from STRUCTURAL_WINNER to FORCE_RIDER. This is the strongest FORCE_RIDER in the entire batch and would rank top 8 in the full 293-model inventory.

scored_cards.model_name: Classified Environment AI Deployment Platform (IL5/IL6)

SN.justification: Baumol 2.36x for cloud computing (518210). $13.4B DoD AI budget but 95% of AI tools can't deploy to classified. Gap between commercial AI and classified deployment is the #1 bottleneck. FedRAMP/ATO moat is extreme.

FA.justification: F1 (10 — open-source LLMs enable air-gapped deployment), F3 (10 — great power competition demands classified AI). Only 2 forces but both at MAXIMUM. Narrower force alignment but absolute intensity.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (FedRAMP cloud + TEMPEST hardware). Regulatory contagion is maximum (10) — FedRAMP IS the product. Competitive very low (5 entrants). Leading indicators very strong (every DoD AI program). Talent is the constraint (TS/SCI cleared AI engineers extremely scarce).

TG.justification: Very high time sensitivity — first to ATO captures multi-year incumbency. High crash resilience (national security imperative). Maven 100% machine-generated by mid-2026 creates immediate demand.

CE.justification: $5-20M capital, 12mo to revenue — longest ramp in the defense batch. 70% gross margins. Cleared personnel requirements add cost. But enterprise contract values ($5-50M) are massive once achieved.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 78.5 >= 70.0, FA 8.0 >= 7.0. Also TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 8.5 >= 8.0). SN 8.0 < 9.0 prevents STRUCTURAL_WINNER. 12mo to revenue is the key constraint.

scored_cards.model_name: Counter-UAS AI Detection and Defeat Platform

SN.justification: Baumol 1.77x for defense electronics. Counter-UAS is existentially necessary (Ukraine proved drones destroy multi-million-dollar vehicles). $7.5B C-UAS budget. 25.8% CAGR. But hardware production complexity and 20 funded entrants create execution risk.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI multi-sensor fusion), F3 (10 — every conflict proves drone threat), F4 (8 — defense tech VC funding). 3 forces, 2 at maximum. Strongest geopolitical validation of any model.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (RF sensors, computing hardware, ITAR components). Regulatory creates moat (ITAR export licensing). Competitive HIGH (20 funded entrants, Anduril/Fortem/DroneShield all well-funded). Leading indicators maximum (10 — Ukraine consumption rates). International demand very strong (NATO allies all need C-UAS).

TG.justification: Replicator 2 procurement window OPEN NOW. High crash resilience (threat-driven, not budget-driven). FEMA grants FY2026. Battlefield reference accounts become de facto standards.

CE.justification: $10-50M capital. 12mo to revenue. 55% gross margins. Does NOT survive 18mo funding freeze. Hardware manufacturing complexity. 20-30 system sales for break-even. Most capital-intensive defense card.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 73.25 >= 70.0, FA 8.0 >= 7.0. Also TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 8.5 >= 8.0). Capital intensity (CE 4.5) is the main constraint preventing higher composite.

scored_cards.model_name: Defense AI Training Simulation Platform (Synthetic Environments)

SN.justification: QCEW 611710 shows Baumol 0.89x — below economy average. Military simulation is $13.4B market growing to $21.1B. STE fielding creates insertion point. But cultural adoption by senior leaders uncertain. Training transfer to real combat unproven.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — generative AI creates scenarios), F3 (8 — evolving threat landscape), F2 (6 — recruitment shortages, Gen Z VR-native). 3 forces, 2 strong. Good alignment but narrower than other defense cards.

EC.justification: Supply chain minimal (software + VR hardware commodity). Regulatory moderate (MIL-STD, TENA accreditation). Competitive moderate (8 funded entrants + legacy CAE/L3Harris). NATO allies create export market. But classified content restrictions limit commercial access.

TG.justification: STE fielding FY2026 creates 2-3 year window. High crash resilience (military training budgets politically sacrosanct). Medium time sensitivity. AI training CHEAPER than live training = attractive in budget pressure.

CE.justification: $3-15M capital, 6mo to revenue, 75% gross margins. 30-50 installations for break-even. 10-100x cost advantage vs live training. Survives funding freeze. Good SaaS platform economics.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 69.5 < 70.0. FA 7.0 meets threshold but composite falls just short. Cultural adoption uncertainty constrains SN and TG.

scored_cards.model_name: Defense Contract Capture AI Platform (SBIR/OTA/IDIQ Navigator)

SN.justification: Baumol 1.82x for management consulting (541611). Defense procurement is Byzantine — real pain point. $49.1B defense tech VC creates wave of startups needing procurement help. But demand is partially time-limited (startup entry wave may plateau) and this is a tool, not a structural necessity.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — LLM proposal generation), F3 (7 — DoD broadening DIB access), F4 (9 — $49.1B defense tech VC is the direct demand driver). 3 forces, 2 strong. Capital flow is the primary force.

EC.justification: Supply chain minimal (pure software). Regulatory complexity IS the value prop (FAR/DFARS). Competitive moderate (6 funded entrants + Govini/Deltek). Leading indicators strong (SBIR solicitation volume). Resource talent available (retired contracting officers).

TG.justification: Wave of defense tech startups entering procurement NOW. First platform captures this cohort. Medium crash resilience — if defense tech VC cools, demand slows. HIGH time sensitivity.

CE.justification: $1-5M capital, 3mo to revenue, 85% gross margins. 200-300 subscriptions for break-even targeting funded startups. 10-20x cost advantage vs capture management consultants. Exceptional unit economics.

scored_cards.category_rationale: Composite 72.25 >= 70.0, FA 7.0 >= 7.0. Also TIMING_ARBITRAGE (TG 8.0 >= 8.0) and CAPITAL_MOAT (CE 9.0 >= 9.0, SN 6.5 >= 6.0).

scored_cards.model_name: Defense Equipment Predictive Maintenance AI (Tactical Edge)

SN.justification: QCEW 336992 shows Baumol 1.24x (low) but only 8.6K employees and 101 establishments — very concentrated. The real driver is DoD $5B/yr maintenance savings and demonstrated 85%->95% uptime. Equipment readiness is a congressional metric. Palantir $85.1M AMC contract validates market.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — edge AI chips enable DDIL inference), F3 (8 — equipment readiness is combat capability), F2 (6 — maintenance workforce aging). 3 forces, 2 strong. DDIL edge deployment is the key differentiator.

EC.justification: Supply chain moderate (edge hardware, sensors — commodity). Regulatory creates moat (MIL-STD, cybersecurity). Competitive moderate (10 funded entrants, Palantir is strong incumbent). NATO allies create export market. Leading indicators strong (AMC contracts).

TG.justification: Market developing with large contracts (Palantir $85.1M). High crash resilience (equipment maintenance mandatory, readiness politically non-negotiable). Medium time sensitivity — edge AI capability is differentiator vs cloud-only.

CE.justification: $3-15M capital, 9mo to revenue, 70% gross margins. 3-5 fleet contracts for break-even. Survives funding freeze. Hardware edge component adds cost but differentiates.

scored_cards.model_name: Defense AI Testing, Evaluation, and Verification Platform (T&E-as-a-Service)

SN.justification: QCEW 541380 shows Baumol 1.28x with 175K employees. DoD AI Strategy mandates T&E. NDAA FY2026 requires AI safety framework. Every dollar of $13.4B AI budget requires T&E. Zero fear friction. No standardized platform exists — greenfield structural necessity within defense.

FA.justification: F1 (9 — AI can test AI), F3 (8 — adversary AI creates urgency). Only 2 forces but both near maximum. Narrow force alignment but absolute intensity within defense context.

EC.justification: Supply chain minimal (pure software). Regulatory contagion maximum (10 — DoD AI Strategy and NDAA mandate T&E). Competitive very low (4 — nearly greenfield). Leading indicators very strong (9). Talent is scarce constraint (AI safety + defense T&E intersection).

cross_source_analysis.defense_premium: Defense cards average 74.8 composite vs 71.6 (v35) and 68.9 (education). This premium is driven by: (1) $13.4B dedicated budget insulated from economic cycles, (2) regulatory moats (ITAR, FedRAMP, CMMC, clearances) that protect first movers, (3) low fear friction (buyers WANT AI), and (4) geopolitical urgency creating counter-cyclical demand.
cross_source_analysis.education_discount: Education cards average 68.9 — lowest of the three sources. This discount is entirely explained by fear friction: education has the LARGEST gap between economic readiness and psychological readiness (gap = 5). The corporate/professional channel (CORP-01: 74.5, TEACH-01: 72.25, CERT-01: 71.0, FEAR-01: 72.25) scores well; the consumer/student-facing channel (TUTOR-01: 62.25) scores lowest due to parental fear.
cross_source_analysis.v35_breadth: V35 cards span 16 sectors with diverse architectures. The financial services models (5239-001: 78.75, 5259-001: 77.25, 5223-001: 78.5) score highest due to 73% AI adoption (lowest friction) + Baumol scores of 2-3.6x + counter-cyclical demand. The marketplace models (5417-002: 64.75) and discretionary consulting model (5416-001: 63.75) score lowest due to cold-start risk and cyclical demand.

calibration_check.vs_existing_inventory: Existing STRUCTURAL_WINNERS score 80.5-84.0. The highest new card (MC-DEF-011: 82.5) would rank in the top 8 of the entire 293-model inventory if it met the SN >= 9.0 threshold. The new cards' mean of 71.7 aligns with the existing inventory mean of 63.1 — the deep dive cards score above average because they were specifically selected for sector depth and architectural specificity, unlike the broad enumeration that includes many thin/speculative models.
